cp||fp||at|^B@2^Y@3T|FP||AT|he following deal is a slight variation of the preceding one, but it contains a somewhat different type of safety play:|PG||NT||
pn|,,,|st||sk|s|md|1sk76hkjt86dk4ca75,sqt3ha2dq2CQJT982,SA84HQ753DA53CK43,SJ952H94DJT9876C6|rh||AH|SAFETY PLAYS BOARD 2|mb|1h2c3hp4hppp|NT|^B@2
With neither side vulnerable, the bidding has gone as shown above and West opens the club Queen,|pc|cQ|pg||at| which North wins with the King, East dropping the six and South the five.|PG||pc|cK|pc|c6|pc|c5|at| The play of the club King from Dummy is a safety play, because the Declarer's greatest fear is again that East's club holding may be a singleton.|PG||AT| This time South cannot avoid losing a trump trick immediately because the Opponents hold the Ace.|PG||NT|^B@2
West is almost certain to obtain the lead on the first round of trumps. Therefore, if South should obey his natural impulse and win the first trick in his own hand, West would be able to lead the Jack of clubs and East's trump would kill Dummy's King of clubs. By taking the King out of the Dummy immediately, South renders the ruff harmless, ^*Ias he can play low from both hands.|PG||NT|^B@2
At the second trick, the trey of hearts is played from Dummy, on which East plays the four, South the Ten and West wins with the Ace.|PG||pc|h3|pc|h4|pc|hT|pc|hA|pg||at| West's return, as expected, is the club Jack, on which the trey is played from the Dummy, and when East ruffs with the nine of hearts, South is able to play the seven of clubs—retaining his Ace to win the third round of the suit.|PG||pc|cJ|pc|c3|pc|h9|pc|c7|pg||NT|^B@2
East is forced to ruff worthless clubs, but if the King remained in the Dummy till the second round, East's ruff would have killed it.|PG||AT| Of course, East could refuse to ruff,|sk||at| but South's Ace would then win, and he would lose but 1 club trick anyway. By making the safety play of Dummy's King on the first trick, South is sure that his club losers will be held to 1 trick. He makes his contract without trouble this way.|PG||sc|y|sk||mc|10|pg||NT|^B@2
This very important safety principle is frequently mishandled. Whenever the Declarer is in danger of a ruff, he should try to arrange his play so that the ruff does as little harm as possible. |PG||UP|12|pf|Y|sc||nt||CP|8|at|^B@2
