pc|s8|pc|h5|pc|hJ|pc|h3|pg||mc|9|pg||UP|24|NT|^B@2
If an aside may be permitted at this point, the preceding deal has considerable interest from the point of view of the Defending Side. If West could only read the Declarer's hand, he would abandon spades at the second trick and lead a heart—when the contract will be defeated. The Declarer must stay off of two rounds of hearts in order to strip the West hand of this suit, but if he does this the defense should shift back to spades. The second shift will make South's defeat a certainty.|PG||NT|^B@2
